    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-02-04T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-02-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="791"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d791">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/1277</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Chinese Minister</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sze</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="27" xml:id="d791fn27">The same, in substance, to the
                        Japanese Ambassador (file no. 793.94/1278).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-02-04">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 4, 1922</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to acknowledge the receipt of
                    the note of February 1, 1922, in which, on behalf of the Chinese Delegation, you
                    were so good as to acquaint me that the conversations between the Chinese and
                    Japanese Delegations on the Shantung question have resulted in complete
                    accord.</p>
                <p>It has given me much satisfaction to receive this welcome intelligence and I
                    sincerely trust that the agreements which the two Delegations have reached will
                    prove of lasting benefit to the two countries.</p>
                <p>In extending to you, and through you to the other members of the Chinese
                    Delegation, my congratulations on the successful conclusion of this arduous and
                    delicate task, I beg leave to express my thanks to you for having communicated
                    to me the substance of the terms agreed upon respecting the various issues
                    involved in the matter in time to permit of my spreading them upon the record of
                    the Fifth Plenary Session of the Conference on the Limitation of Armament.</p>
                <p>Accept [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Charles E. Hughes</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
